WEBVTT

00:20.400 --> 00:23.400
JASPER: Morning, mother,
Stefanie.

00:23.400 --> 00:25.200
I did ask everyone
to be punctual.

00:25.200 --> 00:27.080
-But, uh...
-Yes, thank you very much, uh...

00:27.080 --> 00:28.680
It's not a board meeting,
Jasper.

00:28.680 --> 00:30.000
How are you, Mammy?

00:30.000 --> 00:31.960
I'm fine, I'm really fine,
thank you.

00:31.960 --> 00:33.600
Happy birthday, Granny.

00:33.600 --> 00:36.200
Ditto, uh, I'll be right there.

00:36.200 --> 00:37.960
I'm afraid you're gonna have
to forgive Celia.

00:37.960 --> 00:40.200
She's not having
one of her better days.

00:40.200 --> 00:42.200
Are you?

00:42.200 --> 00:44.880
There were ducks
on the pond, you know?

00:44.880 --> 00:46.720
Bloody hate ducks.

00:46.720 --> 00:49.680
Right. Thank you, Alistair.
That'll be all.

00:49.680 --> 00:52.680
Okay, everybody.

00:52.680 --> 00:56.360
Happy birthday to you

00:56.440 --> 01:00.560
Happy birthday to you

01:00.560 --> 01:06.200
Happy birthday, dear mother

01:06.200 --> 01:09.960
Happy birthday to you

01:09.960 --> 01:11.640
Happy birthday, mother.

01:11.640 --> 01:13.400
For she's
a jolly good fellow

01:13.400 --> 01:14.960
For she's a jolly
good fellow

01:14.960 --> 01:17.520
Uh, no, no, thank you, Chloe.
Uh, that's plenty.

01:17.520 --> 01:19.440
Ma doesn't like fuss,
do you, ma?

01:19.440 --> 01:20.920
Well, I don't mind.

01:20.920 --> 01:23.200
That's really rude
actually, Uncle Jasper.

01:23.200 --> 01:24.440
I was just going to sing her --

01:24.440 --> 01:25.600
No, no, I'll get
back to you, Chloe.

01:25.600 --> 01:27.480
It's just as Ma's first born,

01:27.480 --> 01:30.960
I want to say a few words
on her 83rd birthday.

01:30.960 --> 01:33.600
Uh, Ma, I'm sorry
I can't be there in person,

01:33.600 --> 01:35.200
but, uh, with the divorce,
Helene is being

01:35.200 --> 01:37.000
an absolute nightmare.

01:37.000 --> 01:38.720
I'm sure you'll understand.

01:38.720 --> 01:41.200
Mm, I do understand, Jasper.

01:41.200 --> 01:43.200
But I wish you'd reconsider.

01:43.200 --> 01:46.520
I mean, one failed marriage
is bad enough. But two!

01:46.520 --> 01:48.720
We did all say the age
difference would be

01:48.720 --> 01:50.640
an issue one day.

01:50.640 --> 01:52.240
You'll want to brush up
on your PokÃ©mon characters,

01:52.240 --> 01:54.200
Uncle Jasper, or you'll have
nothing to talk

01:54.200 --> 01:56.440
to your third wife about.
[ Laughs ]

01:56.440 --> 01:58.760
Is that supposed
to be funny, hm?

01:58.760 --> 02:00.360
Bastard ducks.

02:00.360 --> 02:02.920
Shoot the lot of them I say.

02:02.920 --> 02:04.840
Anyway, enough of that.

02:04.840 --> 02:06.760
I have something to say.

02:06.760 --> 02:08.960
I've come to a decision.

02:08.960 --> 02:10.120
Who's there with you, Mammy?

02:10.120 --> 02:11.720
-Who is that?
-Why, no one.

02:11.720 --> 02:12.920
I'm here on my own.

02:12.920 --> 02:14.520
Then who's behind you?

02:14.520 --> 02:16.880
Now, please -- [ Gasps ]

02:16.880 --> 02:18.720
-[ Screams ]
-Oh, my God!

02:20.440 --> 02:23.040
-Mummy!
-Grandmam!

02:23.040 --> 02:26.080
Stop! Stop!

02:28.240 --> 02:30.240
Ma, Mammy!

02:54.480 --> 02:56.200
[ Birds chirping ]

02:56.200 --> 02:59.480
-You are such a snob!
-How dare you.

02:59.480 --> 03:01.760
It's nothing to do with him,
it's to do with you.

03:01.760 --> 03:03.640
What the hell's going on?

03:03.640 --> 03:05.720
Mam doesn't like me
seeing a scanger like Fergus.

03:05.720 --> 03:08.200
That is a horrible word.
I never used that word.

03:08.200 --> 03:11.000
And for the last time,
it's not about that!

03:11.000 --> 03:14.160
-She got a C.
-One C.

03:14.160 --> 03:15.960
Why don't we all just calm down
and discuss this rationally?

03:15.960 --> 03:17.920
There's nothing to discuss.

03:17.920 --> 03:20.880
Look, her studies are slipping.
I've said no more boys.

03:20.880 --> 03:23.600
Except it isn't boys, is it?

03:23.600 --> 03:26.680
It's one specific boy
from the wrong area.

03:26.680 --> 03:30.360
Alright, since you brought it
up, what does his father do?

03:30.360 --> 03:31.840
Exactly.

03:31.840 --> 03:35.160
Look, boys like that
will just hold you back.

03:35.160 --> 03:38.240
You're not to see him again,
Lola, that is my final word.

03:42.480 --> 03:46.080
It's not fair.
I thought you liked Fergus.

03:46.080 --> 03:49.440
Uh, well if your school
work's suffering...

03:49.440 --> 03:51.000
You're as bad as her.

03:54.200 --> 03:55.600
[ Dog barking ]

04:04.080 --> 04:05.720
-[ Clears throat ]
-What's wrong?

04:05.720 --> 04:07.160
What's that?

04:07.160 --> 04:09.480
Those are my
Junior Cert results.

04:09.480 --> 04:11.200
Well, did you pass?

04:11.200 --> 04:14.200
Don't know.
I haven't opened them yet.

04:14.200 --> 04:15.640
What if I failed?

04:15.640 --> 04:17.400
Well, you never cared
about exams before,

04:17.400 --> 04:19.640
but now you do
because Harry does.

04:19.640 --> 04:21.400
Stop that.

04:21.400 --> 04:24.520
You're 7. You're not
supposed to be so insightful.

04:24.520 --> 04:26.800
And you never used words
like "insightful."

04:26.800 --> 04:29.440
Just open it.

04:29.440 --> 04:31.000
Okay.

04:33.440 --> 04:35.960
[ Cellphone rings ]

04:40.880 --> 04:43.680
Uh, this is work, Libs.

04:43.680 --> 04:45.040
What work?

04:49.520 --> 04:52.160
[ Clears throat ]

04:52.160 --> 04:56.080
Wild Reid Detective Agency.
How I may I direct your call?

04:57.640 --> 04:59.240
Mm-hmm.

04:59.240 --> 05:00.840
Okay.

05:09.000 --> 05:12.200
-Mm-mm, fine boy.
-Thank you.

05:12.200 --> 05:14.480
Uh, has a lady been
in asking for me?

05:14.480 --> 05:15.840
You know you're not really
supposed to be

05:15.840 --> 05:17.000
in here alone right?

05:17.000 --> 05:19.200
I'm not alone.

05:19.200 --> 05:20.760
I'm with Glenn.

05:20.760 --> 05:22.400
Huh?

05:22.400 --> 05:24.960
Oh, yeah, that's right, uh,
I'm his guest.

05:24.960 --> 05:26.720
I'll have another, he's buying.

05:26.720 --> 05:28.040
He bloody well isn't.

05:28.040 --> 05:29.520
June, has anyone been in?

05:29.520 --> 05:31.000
Yes.

05:31.000 --> 05:32.560
In the corner.

05:38.760 --> 05:40.680
FERGUS: Harry.

05:40.680 --> 05:42.200
There is someone
you need to meet.

05:42.200 --> 05:43.680
What?
Can't I have a drink first?

05:43.680 --> 05:46.040
No, no, no, no, no.
Someone you need to meet.

05:51.640 --> 05:54.600
Miss Henderson.
Harry Wild, Fergus Reid.

05:54.600 --> 05:57.720
We spoke on the phone.

05:57.720 --> 05:59.400
Is this a joke?

05:59.400 --> 06:01.240
You're detectives?

06:01.240 --> 06:03.960
We have a lot of experience
actually.

06:03.960 --> 06:06.400
Caught a killer in this pub
as it goes,

06:06.400 --> 06:08.520
the night of the big storm.

06:08.520 --> 06:10.680
STEFANIE:
Oh, that was you, was it?

06:10.680 --> 06:12.840
I remember reading about that.

06:16.240 --> 06:19.160
Um, Miss Henderson,
I-I must warn you

06:19.160 --> 06:23.360
that we are very much
in demand at the moment.

06:23.360 --> 06:25.560
More than even I knew.

06:25.560 --> 06:28.640
And we are very selective
about the clients we work with.

06:28.640 --> 06:30.640
Well, when I tell you
what happened,

06:30.640 --> 06:33.680
I guarantee you'll want
to take my case.

06:39.840 --> 06:42.520
I've, uh, written some
basic details

06:42.520 --> 06:45.000
about the family
and what happened.

06:45.000 --> 06:47.480
I didn't want to miss anything.

06:47.480 --> 06:51.000
If only all our clients
were so organized.

06:51.000 --> 06:52.360
What did happen?

06:52.360 --> 06:54.040
It was my mother's birthday.

06:54.040 --> 06:55.240
She lives...

06:55.240 --> 06:58.120
lived here, as do I.

06:58.120 --> 07:00.680
But the rest of the family
are all over in, um,

07:00.680 --> 07:03.240
London and Edinburgh, Paris.

07:03.240 --> 07:06.520
So we arranged a video call
during which a burglar

07:06.520 --> 07:08.440
broke into
my mother's house and...

07:12.800 --> 07:14.960
It was awful.

07:14.960 --> 07:17.120
And the Guards
are utterly useless.

07:17.120 --> 07:21.720
It's her funeral tomorrow,
and they haven't got anywhere.

07:21.720 --> 07:23.680
Actually come to think of it,
the inspector in charge

07:23.680 --> 07:26.400
is called Wild.

07:26.400 --> 07:29.400
Oh, it's a very common name.

07:29.400 --> 07:32.400
Like Henderson,
there's plenty of them.

07:32.400 --> 07:35.760
I mean, like, um,
Peter Henderson.

07:35.760 --> 07:39.600
Writes those bloody awful
Jonny Bowman spy books

07:39.600 --> 07:42.680
they keep making movies of.

07:42.680 --> 07:45.440
Peter Henderson was my father.

07:45.440 --> 07:48.080
Author of those bloody
awful Jonny Bowman spy books.

07:51.480 --> 07:53.760
Ah, awkward. [ Chuckles ]

07:53.760 --> 07:56.800
They're very popular.

07:56.800 --> 07:59.880
So, the family has money?

07:59.880 --> 08:02.680
We can afford to pay
if that's what you're asking.

08:02.680 --> 08:04.440
It's not actually.

08:04.440 --> 08:07.120
Money can be a strong motive
for murder.

08:07.120 --> 08:10.240
Hm, thinking like
a true detective.

08:10.240 --> 08:17.480
Uh, as per your website,
the 5,000 euro retainer.

08:17.480 --> 08:19.720
Thank you, Miss Henderson.

08:19.720 --> 08:23.960
I have all your details.
We'll be in touch.

08:23.960 --> 08:26.280
-Thank you.
-Thank you.

08:32.440 --> 08:35.200
Well, a few minute's warning
would have been nice.

08:35.200 --> 08:38.600
I thought you might say no.

08:38.600 --> 08:40.240
How did you manage this?

08:40.240 --> 08:41.880
It's actually easier
than you think.

08:41.880 --> 08:44.200
You know, you just fill out
a few forms online,

08:44.200 --> 08:46.200
and then you watch
a YouTube tutorial

08:46.200 --> 08:48.920
on search engine
optimization and...

08:48.920 --> 08:50.520
Very impressive.

08:50.520 --> 08:53.360
Okay, we'll take this case
and just see how it goes.

08:53.360 --> 08:56.200
But no promises.

08:56.200 --> 08:57.440
Yeah, I'm not actually
old enough

08:57.440 --> 08:58.680
to open a business account.

08:58.680 --> 09:00.560
So do you mind?

09:03.920 --> 09:05.440
Any sign of your exam results?

09:05.440 --> 09:08.600
Shouldn't they have come
in by now?

09:08.600 --> 09:11.080
Uh, yeah maybe,
maybe they came today.

09:11.080 --> 09:16.480
I mean, I was out before
the postman arrived so...

09:16.480 --> 09:18.080
I'll tell June
you're gasping, yeah?

09:33.920 --> 09:36.120
Oh, mother of divine Jesus.

09:53.360 --> 09:56.120
[ Indistinct chatter ]

10:06.200 --> 10:08.520
Now, Celia, can I get you
anything else?

10:08.520 --> 10:11.040
Uh, a cushion, some entrees?

10:13.520 --> 10:15.080
No.

10:43.080 --> 10:45.040
Would you like a glass
of your own?

10:50.800 --> 10:53.080
Do you do that a lot?

10:53.080 --> 10:54.440
Only when I can't be bothered
to have

10:54.440 --> 10:57.520
another feckin'
dreary conversation.

10:57.520 --> 11:00.240
And funerals are nothing but.

11:00.240 --> 11:02.520
Might perk up later
when everyone's sizzled.

11:02.520 --> 11:05.400
[ Laughs ]

11:05.400 --> 11:08.720
Are you really
a private detective?

11:08.720 --> 11:10.640
Like on the telly?

11:10.640 --> 11:14.240
Are you going to trick me into
dishing the dirt on my family?

11:14.240 --> 11:17.600
Because I will, happily.

11:17.600 --> 11:19.640
Let's see now, my nephew

11:19.640 --> 11:22.840
Jasper is a swine
when it comes to women.

11:22.840 --> 11:27.360
Dumped his first wife like a cup
of cold sick for his secretary.

11:27.360 --> 11:29.200
That old clichÃ©.

11:29.200 --> 11:32.440
Rumor is he's found himself
an even younger model now.

11:32.440 --> 11:34.480
Noah made some joke
about it on the call

11:34.480 --> 11:36.600
when my sister was killed.

11:36.600 --> 11:39.880
Now, Stefanie owns
a string of bakeries.

11:39.880 --> 11:42.680
But they're losing money
like there was no tomorrow.

11:42.680 --> 11:46.480
She never married.
Noah and Chloe are both adopted.

11:46.480 --> 11:48.200
Stefanie's a lesbian.

11:48.200 --> 11:49.680
She's gay?

11:49.680 --> 11:52.840
Oh as a row of tents
but would never admit it.

11:52.840 --> 11:54.960
Ridiculous in this day and age.

11:54.960 --> 11:58.440
Young people nowadays think
they invented homosexuality.

11:58.440 --> 12:00.640
Who hasn't had a bit of fanny
in their time?

12:00.640 --> 12:02.520
I know I have.

12:02.520 --> 12:04.920
Quite.

12:04.920 --> 12:07.720
CELIA: Noah's a right old
mammy's boy.

12:07.720 --> 12:09.520
Utterly spineless.

12:09.520 --> 12:11.520
It's okay, I-I got the salt
and vinegar that you...

12:11.520 --> 12:13.240
I asked for salt
five minutes ago.

12:13.240 --> 12:14.480
I thought you said
you wanted --

12:14.480 --> 12:15.760
CELIA: Chloe's
the exact opposite.

12:15.760 --> 12:18.400
Noah wouldn't say boo
to a goose.

12:18.400 --> 12:21.880
Chloe would chase the goose
down and kick it in the balls.

12:21.880 --> 12:24.120
And not even for any
particular reason.

12:24.120 --> 12:26.880
She's a destructive
little thing.

12:26.880 --> 12:29.080
I happen to know that Noah

12:29.080 --> 12:32.760
owes a great deal of money
to Russian gamblers.

12:32.760 --> 12:34.760
Poker's his game,

12:34.760 --> 12:37.200
but he's fecking useless
at it apparently.

12:37.200 --> 12:38.680
I heard him whining to Bella

12:38.680 --> 12:40.760
that they're going to
cut of his willy.

12:40.760 --> 12:44.480
Didn't think I was
paying attention, but I was.

12:44.480 --> 12:46.960
Bella is an angel.

12:46.960 --> 12:49.600
The only one who visits me.

12:49.600 --> 12:51.680
I do hope it wasn't her.

12:51.680 --> 12:54.200
You think one of the family
killed Susan?

12:54.200 --> 12:56.240
Isn't that why you're here?

12:56.240 --> 12:59.880
Well, how could they if they
were all on the same call?

12:59.880 --> 13:01.760
Well, that I don't know.

13:01.760 --> 13:07.000
But I do know that they're all
desperate for the inheritance.

13:08.200 --> 13:10.040
Any chance of more wine?

13:11.760 --> 13:13.600
[ Chuckles ]

13:15.360 --> 13:16.880
Stuck up cow.

13:16.880 --> 13:19.200
I'm about to be a very rich man.

13:19.200 --> 13:20.760
You could do a lot worse.

13:34.440 --> 13:37.640
I just overheard a very
interesting conversation.

13:37.640 --> 13:39.840
And I'm in the middle of one.
Come on.

13:39.840 --> 13:41.920
So I've just hear Alistair,
the nurse,

13:41.920 --> 13:43.240
boasting about what...

13:43.240 --> 13:44.760
Alistair?

13:44.760 --> 13:48.080
He's a duplicitous little shit.

13:48.080 --> 13:50.760
But he's not very bright,
so I keep him around.

13:50.760 --> 13:54.360
He steals from me.

13:54.360 --> 13:55.920
Yorgos?

13:58.800 --> 14:00.200
Fergus.

14:00.200 --> 14:02.760
Oh, I don't believe it.

14:02.760 --> 14:05.400
You haven't changed a bit.

14:05.400 --> 14:09.440
Oh, Yorgos, it must be more than
30 years since we walked along

14:09.440 --> 14:11.960
Kalamaki beach at sunset.

14:11.960 --> 14:13.880
And you...

14:13.880 --> 14:16.000
[ Whispering indistinctly ]

14:19.120 --> 14:22.480
That does not sound
very hygienic.

14:22.480 --> 14:24.880
Oh, Harry!

14:24.880 --> 14:26.280
I think it might be time to go.

14:37.600 --> 14:40.440
[ Clears throat ]

14:44.760 --> 14:46.600
Oh, shite!

14:46.600 --> 14:47.840
Ah...

14:50.040 --> 14:52.320
[ Grunts ] Ow!

14:55.920 --> 14:58.480
[ Sniffs ]

15:03.360 --> 15:06.040
[ Sniffs ]

15:06.040 --> 15:07.720
Sorry, I had...

15:07.720 --> 15:09.200
Oh, it's you.

15:09.200 --> 15:10.960
Who were you expecting?

15:10.960 --> 15:12.800
No one.

15:12.800 --> 15:14.200
Can this wait?

15:14.200 --> 15:16.760
It's just that I'm...

15:16.760 --> 15:19.680
Uh, I'm...bushed.

15:19.680 --> 15:22.360
No, it can't.
It won't take long.

15:25.480 --> 15:26.720
[ Sniffs ]

15:26.720 --> 15:28.280
Can you smell curry?

15:31.680 --> 15:33.040
[ Sniffs ]

15:34.200 --> 15:36.200
[ Door closes ]

15:36.200 --> 15:38.440
Why were you there?

15:38.440 --> 15:39.840
Why were you there?

15:39.840 --> 15:41.520
I was there in
an official capacity.

15:41.520 --> 15:43.640
And we were, too.

15:43.640 --> 15:46.240
The family are entitled to hire
private investigators.

15:46.240 --> 15:47.720
Private investigators?

15:47.720 --> 15:48.720
You and F--

15:51.200 --> 15:53.640
[ Scoffs ] Why do you
hate me so much?

15:53.640 --> 15:55.760
Don't be so melodramatic.

15:55.760 --> 15:57.680
I suppose you know about
Jasper's divorce

15:57.680 --> 16:00.400
and Stefanie's business failing,
but did you know that

16:00.400 --> 16:03.680
Noah owes a lot of money
to some Russian gamblers?

16:03.680 --> 16:05.760
All in desperate need of cash.

16:05.760 --> 16:07.440
And all have
a pretty good alibi.

16:07.440 --> 16:09.080
Well, they could have
hired someone.

16:09.080 --> 16:10.680
And paid them how?
We've checked.

16:10.680 --> 16:13.720
No unusual payments, no one
sending large sums of money.

16:13.720 --> 16:16.240
Hired killers don't tend
to work on a promise.

16:16.240 --> 16:18.480
Interesting.
I didn't know that.

16:18.480 --> 16:20.880
[ Groans ] I got to go.

16:20.880 --> 16:23.320
There's a wall that needs me
to beat my head against it.

16:44.000 --> 16:45.960
Oh.

16:45.960 --> 16:48.960
I'm a superintendent, Harry.

16:48.960 --> 16:52.880
That's not very dignified,
messing around in bushes.

16:52.880 --> 16:54.600
That's not what you usually say.

16:54.600 --> 16:55.920
[ Both laugh ]

17:00.120 --> 17:02.640
There's something going on
with Ray.

17:02.640 --> 17:07.960
He seems different, happy.

17:07.960 --> 17:12.000
I mean, what's he got
to be happy about?

17:12.000 --> 17:14.000
I want you to find out for me.

17:15.640 --> 17:16.920
Now?

17:16.920 --> 17:19.440
No, of course not now.

17:19.440 --> 17:21.000
Later.

17:27.240 --> 17:28.800
Much later.

17:42.520 --> 17:45.000
Alistair is well shifty.

17:45.000 --> 17:48.160
That is a 60,000 euro car.

17:48.160 --> 17:51.600
How much money does he think
he's getting?

17:51.600 --> 17:53.720
Charlie said
something interesting.

17:53.720 --> 17:56.480
Professional killers won't work
on a promise.

17:56.480 --> 17:58.120
But amateur ones may.

17:58.120 --> 17:59.240
Yeah, but the thing
is according to

17:59.240 --> 18:02.160
Stefanie's notes,
he was on the call, too.

18:02.160 --> 18:05.400
She said he was only on the call
in the beginning.

18:05.400 --> 18:09.960
Now, I drove from Susan's house
to Celia's nursing home earlier.

18:09.960 --> 18:13.240
It only takes minutes.

18:13.240 --> 18:16.000
You think one of them agreed
to pay him

18:16.000 --> 18:18.000
when they get the inheritance?

18:18.000 --> 18:20.640
Maybe, we'll see.

18:20.640 --> 18:23.960
They're reading the will
this afternoon.

18:23.960 --> 18:26.160
BERNARD: [ Clears throat ]

18:26.160 --> 18:28.720
Well, before we begin
I think it only fair

18:28.720 --> 18:31.480
to tell you
that in recent months

18:31.480 --> 18:34.760
Susan altered her will.

18:38.240 --> 18:40.720
Altered it?

18:40.720 --> 18:42.280
Altered it how?

18:45.480 --> 18:46.680
[ Clears throat ]

18:48.640 --> 18:52.440
Forget why I hired you.

18:52.440 --> 18:54.600
Right now I don't care
who killed my bloody mother.

18:54.600 --> 18:55.920
I wish I had!

18:55.920 --> 18:58.680
She's liquidated it all.

18:58.680 --> 19:01.360
All the investments
my father set up.

19:01.360 --> 19:07.360
She closed bank accounts,
she sold most of the property.

19:07.360 --> 19:11.720
It all adds up to over
10 million euros.

19:11.720 --> 19:14.000
And no one knows where it is.

19:14.000 --> 19:16.280
So I want you to stop looking
for the killer

19:16.280 --> 19:18.680
and start looking
for the money.

19:18.680 --> 19:20.800
You didn't get anything?

19:20.800 --> 19:24.640
STEFANIE: Oh, no, I did.

19:24.640 --> 19:27.000
Embroideries.

19:27.000 --> 19:28.760
It was her latest hobby.

19:28.760 --> 19:30.520
That's all any of us got.

19:30.520 --> 19:33.520
Well, apart from Chloe,
who got some books.

19:33.520 --> 19:35.360
Oh, oh, not the first editions,

19:35.360 --> 19:36.680
which were actually
worth something.

19:36.680 --> 19:38.760
No, she sold those.

19:38.760 --> 19:43.880
And poor Bella,
all she got was one wig,

19:43.880 --> 19:45.840
and it was the one mammy
was cremated in,

19:45.840 --> 19:49.400
so she didn't even get that.

19:49.400 --> 19:54.000
My mother went bloody mental,
and none of us noticed.

19:54.440 --> 19:57.120
Date's wrong.
It's Liberty's favorite film,

19:57.120 --> 19:58.920
so I've seen it more times
than is healthy,

19:58.920 --> 20:03.280
but Titanic sank in 1912,
not 1911.

20:03.280 --> 20:05.080
April 15th I think it was.

20:05.080 --> 20:08.680
Bastille Day is 14th of July.
Even I know that.

20:08.680 --> 20:10.840
But I don't know what year.

20:10.840 --> 20:14.280
-Well, I can look it up.
-Oh, 1789.

20:14.280 --> 20:16.480
Brush up on your Dickens.

20:16.480 --> 20:18.240
"Tale of Two Cities."

20:18.240 --> 20:21.240
"It was the best of times,
it was the worst of times."

20:21.240 --> 20:25.080
Well, this is the bloody
worst of times.

20:25.080 --> 20:29.760
I have inherited some factually
incorrect embroideries.

20:29.760 --> 20:31.680
She liked her games.

20:31.680 --> 20:35.200
She liked screwing with people.

20:35.200 --> 20:38.480
My father's books,
all 22 of them.

20:38.480 --> 20:40.200
One every year.

20:40.200 --> 20:42.200
Regular as clockwork.

20:42.200 --> 20:43.760
What about the wigs?

20:47.920 --> 20:49.480
Hm.

20:53.200 --> 20:57.280
Uh, that was where
Bella's one was.

20:57.280 --> 21:00.680
All films named after women.

21:00.680 --> 21:02.840
What was the name
on the missing wig?

21:02.840 --> 21:04.720
Oh, I don't know.
I never noticed.

21:04.720 --> 21:07.120
She just called it here
"Fun Time Wig."

21:18.400 --> 21:22.760
Just treating my inheritance
with the respect it deserves.

21:22.760 --> 21:24.120
What are they about?

21:24.120 --> 21:27.600
Well, you take a dash
of James Bond

21:27.600 --> 21:29.560
and a sprinkling
of Simon Templar.

21:29.560 --> 21:31.640
Stick in a bird with big tits
who lets Jonny Bowman shag her

21:31.640 --> 21:35.600
the first time
they meet, and voilÃ .

21:35.600 --> 21:37.400
Sound all right.

21:37.400 --> 21:40.480
Ah, it was the bird
with big tits, wasn't it?

21:40.480 --> 21:42.520
[ Chuckles ]

21:43.240 --> 21:46.440
Here.

21:46.440 --> 21:48.000
Keep it.

21:48.000 --> 21:50.240
If you like it, there's a whole
bin full of them.

21:54.520 --> 21:56.080
Thanks.

22:05.680 --> 22:07.040
I'm on Alistair now.

22:36.760 --> 22:38.400
Yeah, I lost him.

22:38.400 --> 22:41.280
He went into some fancy
new hotel in Monk Street.

22:41.280 --> 22:43.760
He could be meeting
whoever hired him.

22:43.760 --> 22:45.600
Hm, probably yes.

22:45.600 --> 22:47.200
You'll just have to wait
till he comes out.

22:47.200 --> 22:48.680
How does that help us?

22:48.680 --> 22:51.600
We won't know
who he's been meeting.

22:51.600 --> 22:53.040
Harry, I could go in.

22:53.040 --> 22:54.840
And what?

22:54.840 --> 22:56.880
Knock on every door?

22:56.880 --> 22:58.280
No.

22:58.280 --> 23:00.240
I mean, he might be
meeting them in the bar.

23:00.240 --> 23:02.080
There's a sign that says
there's one on the rooftop.

23:02.080 --> 23:04.000
And I saw him
getting into the lift.

23:04.000 --> 23:06.760
Well, first, he'd see you
and second, you're a teenager.

23:06.760 --> 23:08.400
They wouldn't
let you in anyway.

23:08.400 --> 23:10.080
Alright.

23:10.880 --> 23:12.760
[ Sighs ]

23:12.760 --> 23:15.920
Here look, you haven't spoken to
Lola recently at all, have you?

23:15.920 --> 23:18.400
A few days ago, why?

23:18.400 --> 23:20.000
FERGUS: No reason.

23:20.000 --> 23:23.200
She's just been
ignoring my -- my texts.

23:23.200 --> 23:25.160
And not returning my calls.

23:25.160 --> 23:28.360
Well, I'd expect you to know
more about her than me anyway.

23:28.360 --> 23:30.240
Since the last time
I saw you with her,

23:30.240 --> 23:32.520
she had her tongue
in your mouth.

23:32.520 --> 23:34.400
Oh, Jesus, Harry!

23:34.400 --> 23:36.200
I'm not comfortable having
this conversation with you.

23:36.200 --> 23:37.840
You brought it up.

23:37.840 --> 23:40.160
Yeah, and you made it weird.
I was just --

23:40.160 --> 23:42.120
Oh, Jesus Christ
on a fucking bike!

23:45.480 --> 23:46.960
HARRY: Fergus?

23:46.960 --> 23:49.720
Fergus, what -- what is it?
Are you okay?

23:49.720 --> 23:51.880
What happened?

23:51.880 --> 23:53.640
What -- what -- what is it?
What was it?

23:53.640 --> 23:56.200
Alistair's dead.

23:56.200 --> 23:58.200
Oh, fu--

23:58.200 --> 24:00.040
Oh, shit.

24:09.040 --> 24:11.840
Let's make this quick, hm?

24:11.840 --> 24:12.960
Okay, how did you...?

24:12.960 --> 24:15.400
JASPER: I mean, it's ridiculous.

24:15.400 --> 24:18.640
He's a child, and you're a...

24:18.640 --> 24:23.000
[ Laughs ] No, look, look.

24:23.000 --> 24:24.720
I don't have a gambling problem.

24:24.720 --> 24:27.040
The occasional flutter
in the Grand National maybe,

24:27.040 --> 24:28.640
but who -- who doesn't, eh?

24:28.640 --> 24:30.600
So you don't play poker?

24:30.600 --> 24:32.480
Uh, no, no.

24:32.480 --> 24:35.640
Jesus, no wonder you're in deep
to the Russians.

24:35.640 --> 24:38.760
You want to work
on your poker face.

24:38.760 --> 24:41.000
BELLA: It's sad when you think
about it.

24:41.000 --> 24:43.520
I mean, I've known him
for a donkeys.

24:43.520 --> 24:45.720
He's been Aunty Celia's nurse
for years.

24:45.720 --> 24:48.200
But I didn't know him.

24:48.200 --> 24:51.280
No idea he was depressed.

24:51.280 --> 24:53.120
He was depressed?

24:53.120 --> 24:55.760
He jumped off a building,
didn't he?

24:55.760 --> 24:57.720
Or he was pushed off.

24:57.720 --> 24:59.400
[ Scoffs ]

24:59.400 --> 25:00.920
You know, I can't see him
inspiring that kind

25:00.920 --> 25:03.760
of passion in anyone.

25:03.760 --> 25:08.360
She was a granny, a bit scary,
a bit lovely.

25:08.360 --> 25:10.640
Oh, how could she be
a bit lovely?

25:10.640 --> 25:12.160
CHLOE: I don't know.

25:12.160 --> 25:15.800
Maybe it was just when
she wasn't sniping at me.

25:15.800 --> 25:19.720
Or when we were kids,

25:19.720 --> 25:23.760
she'd always do this incredible
Easter egg hunt.

25:23.760 --> 25:26.000
There'd be clues we had
to decipher,

25:26.000 --> 25:27.520
puzzles we had to solve.

25:27.520 --> 25:29.200
-They were cool.
-Mm.

25:29.200 --> 25:31.600
More games.

25:31.600 --> 25:33.480
There's a rumor that your
father's having an affair

25:33.480 --> 25:35.200
with a younger woman.

25:35.200 --> 25:36.480
Well, ask him.

25:36.480 --> 25:38.040
I mean, it's hardly
the sort of thing

25:38.040 --> 25:40.360
he's going to tell me, is it?

25:40.360 --> 25:42.120
Plus he's like 55.

25:42.120 --> 25:45.680
I mean, can people even still
have sex at that age?

25:45.680 --> 25:47.760
[ Clears throat ]

25:47.760 --> 25:49.760
We have asked him.

25:49.760 --> 25:51.560
And what did he say?

25:51.560 --> 25:53.440
Feck off.

25:53.440 --> 25:55.880
None of your business.

25:55.880 --> 25:57.840
Cheeky little shit.

25:57.840 --> 26:02.160
It's nauseatingly sad,
but Bella wants to be

26:02.160 --> 26:06.080
an Insta-Fluencer
or whatever you call them.

26:06.080 --> 26:07.880
You know, one of those
beautiful people who travel

26:07.880 --> 26:11.560
the world posting photos
on yachts or under waterfalls.

26:11.560 --> 26:14.600
Trouble is, well, apart
from who in their right mind

26:14.600 --> 26:18.560
would want to be influenced
by Bella, it costs money.

26:18.560 --> 26:20.480
You know, to live the life,
you need the followers,

26:20.480 --> 26:24.680
and to get the followers,
you need to live the life.

26:24.680 --> 26:28.200
She asked for an advance
on her inheritance.

26:28.200 --> 26:30.200
BELLA: Laughed me
out of the room.

26:30.200 --> 26:33.120
Uh, I bet Chloe said that.

26:33.120 --> 26:35.920
Granny said she'd think
about it.

26:35.920 --> 26:38.080
Your mother said that you live
in New Town.

26:38.080 --> 26:40.280
That's an expensive
part of Edinburgh.

26:40.280 --> 26:42.680
And that you work
in a shoe store?

26:42.680 --> 26:44.880
We called it.

26:44.880 --> 26:46.640
Why would you do that?

26:46.640 --> 26:49.800
They say that you stopped
working there months ago.

26:49.800 --> 26:52.000
We were just wondering how
you could afford to live there?

26:53.800 --> 26:55.720
I'm a whore.

26:55.720 --> 26:58.240
Part time.

26:58.240 --> 27:01.040
It was much the same
as any other call.

27:01.040 --> 27:07.720
Um, Dad talked over people,
Chloe sulked, um,

27:07.720 --> 27:09.760
Noah made a joke in poor taste,

27:09.760 --> 27:12.960
and Aunty Celia
was there in body only.

27:12.960 --> 27:15.640
Sorry, what does that mean?

27:15.640 --> 27:18.680
Well, she was having
one of her bad days.

27:18.680 --> 27:20.240
She mumbled something
about ducks.

27:20.240 --> 27:22.120
I mean, I think
that was all she said.

27:26.520 --> 27:28.800
It was a nice bicycle.

27:28.800 --> 27:31.240
Had a little bell.

27:31.240 --> 27:32.640
What did you say
your name was, love?

27:32.640 --> 27:34.920
Oh, Fergus.

27:34.920 --> 27:37.520
She was going on and on
about someone called Yorgos.

27:37.520 --> 27:40.040
I'm glad it's not you.
The things she was saying.

27:40.040 --> 27:43.400
Enough to turn my hair white.

27:43.400 --> 27:47.280
We wanted to ask her about
the call where her sister died.

27:47.280 --> 27:50.000
She was having a bad day
then, too.

27:50.000 --> 27:52.640
But she did tell us
some details about it.

27:52.640 --> 27:55.520
Probably watched it back later
when she was feeling better.

27:55.520 --> 27:57.720
Alistair used to record
the calls on her computer

27:57.720 --> 28:00.080
just in case.

28:00.080 --> 28:02.800
Uh, do you mind
if I take a look?

28:02.800 --> 28:04.440
Be my guest.

28:04.440 --> 28:06.000
Isn't he polite?

28:10.880 --> 28:13.200
Hm.

28:13.200 --> 28:15.760
Nothing from the day
of the murder.

28:15.760 --> 28:17.480
Oh, that's right.

28:17.480 --> 28:19.200
Celia did say Alistair
took it off of there

28:19.200 --> 28:20.880
to give it to the guards.

28:20.880 --> 28:24.040
Put it on one of them
little USB drives.

28:24.040 --> 28:25.840
A red one!

28:25.840 --> 28:28.200
Never invite me to your house
because I will rob you.

28:28.200 --> 28:29.720
Can't help meself.
What am I like?

28:29.720 --> 28:32.000
You've been to my house
loads of times, Skeevy.

28:32.000 --> 28:35.200
Yeah, but to be fair, fair, you
have feck all worth stealing.

28:35.200 --> 28:37.000
How long have you been
a burglar, Mr. Callaghan?

28:37.000 --> 28:39.200
Skeevy, please.

28:39.200 --> 28:40.640
Family business.

28:40.640 --> 28:42.280
Me dad's a burglar,
both of me granddads.

28:42.280 --> 28:44.520
All me brothers, except for one.

28:44.520 --> 28:45.960
He's a chartered surveyor.

28:45.960 --> 28:47.200
We don't talk about him.

28:47.200 --> 28:48.760
My mam, she was a shoplifter.

28:48.760 --> 28:51.640
A real Romeo and Juliet story,
my mam and dad.

28:51.640 --> 28:53.280
Sounds very romantic.

28:53.280 --> 28:54.880
So Malky was saying there
was some flat

28:54.880 --> 28:56.560
that you wanted
to have a nose around?

28:56.560 --> 28:58.400
The trouble is that
we're looking for a USB stick.

28:58.400 --> 29:01.080
It's very small,
it could be hidden anywhere.

29:01.080 --> 29:03.280
Yeah, but you see people tend to
hide things in certain places,

29:03.280 --> 29:05.360
and not one
to blow me own trumpet,

29:05.360 --> 29:07.120
but I know all the places.

29:12.120 --> 29:14.960
Good locks these.
Hard to get into.

29:14.960 --> 29:18.360
If you're ever upgrading your
security, I'd recommend these.

29:18.360 --> 29:20.960
I can install them for you
if you want.

29:20.960 --> 29:24.200
You told me never to
invite you to my house.

29:24.200 --> 29:26.440
Good for you.
Paying attention.

29:26.440 --> 29:29.640
[ Lock clicks ]

29:29.640 --> 29:31.040
VoilÃ .

29:41.560 --> 29:43.120
Hm.

29:45.280 --> 29:46.840
Interesting.

29:49.000 --> 29:50.520
That's where he died.

29:54.400 --> 29:56.040
Hm.

30:13.640 --> 30:15.920
Skeevy, you're a marvel.

30:15.920 --> 30:17.280
Ah, get over it. Do you mind
if I swipe his telly?

30:17.280 --> 30:20.200
It's not like he'll need it.

30:20.200 --> 30:22.440
SUSAN: Anyway, enough of that.

30:22.440 --> 30:26.000
I have something to say.
I've come to a decision.

30:26.000 --> 30:28.120
Who's there with you, Mammy?

30:28.120 --> 30:30.000
No one.
I'm here on my own.

30:30.000 --> 30:31.600
STEFANIE: Then who's behind you?

30:31.600 --> 30:34.080
SUSAN: Now please -- [ Gasps ]

30:34.080 --> 30:37.040
-[ Screams ]
-Oh, my God!

30:37.040 --> 30:38.360
-[ Gasps ]
-Grandmam!

30:38.360 --> 30:39.520
JASPER: Stop!

30:40.400 --> 30:42.160
There's no way Alistair
could have got to Susan's

30:42.160 --> 30:44.440
in that time, which means
he wasn't the killer.

30:44.440 --> 30:46.720
But he made a copy of this
and hid it.

30:46.720 --> 30:48.520
I mean, he must have
had a reason.

30:48.520 --> 30:50.400
Blackmail?

30:50.400 --> 30:52.360
Yes, he thought
he was gonna be rich.

30:53.960 --> 30:57.000
[ Cellphone buzzing ]

30:57.000 --> 30:58.960
Look, I got to go and get
Liberty from Annie's.

30:58.960 --> 31:00.680
Can we talk about this later?

31:00.680 --> 31:02.360
Did you fail?

31:02.360 --> 31:03.840
Hm?

31:03.840 --> 31:07.400
Well, everyone's got
their results by now.

31:07.400 --> 31:10.880
I won't be annoyed.
I know how hard you worked.

31:10.880 --> 31:12.760
Look, I don't know
if I failed, okay?

31:12.760 --> 31:15.800
I haven't even opened
the envelope yet.

31:15.800 --> 31:17.280
Why ever not?

31:19.440 --> 31:21.000
In case I failed.

31:24.560 --> 31:28.120
Bring it with you tomorrow, and
we'll open it together, okay?

31:37.040 --> 31:39.520
[ Door opens, closes ]

31:39.520 --> 31:41.920
That's really rude, actually,
Uncle Jasper.

31:41.920 --> 31:43.360
I was just going to sing --

31:43.360 --> 31:44.760
No, no, no, I'll get
back to you, Chloe.

31:44.760 --> 31:46.480
It's just as Ma's first born,

31:46.480 --> 31:50.240
I want to say a few words
on her 83rd birthday.

31:50.240 --> 31:52.480
-[ Knock on door ]
-Look, Ma, I'm sorry I --

31:59.640 --> 32:03.200
Oh, well, if you're looking for
Fergus, you just missed him.

32:03.200 --> 32:05.280
I was waiting for him to leave.

32:05.280 --> 32:06.560
What?

32:08.680 --> 32:10.840
Well, that doesn't sound good.

32:12.400 --> 32:14.560
He says you've been
avoiding him.

32:14.560 --> 32:16.280
Oh, God.

32:16.280 --> 32:17.960
Is that what he thinks?

32:17.960 --> 32:19.640
You haven't been avoiding him?

32:19.640 --> 32:21.760
Oh, well, no, I have.

32:21.760 --> 32:24.240
But it's not my fault.

32:24.240 --> 32:26.960
[ Sighs ] My mom's
being a total bitch.

32:26.960 --> 32:29.280
She told me I'm not allowed
to see him anymore.

32:29.280 --> 32:30.600
Why?

32:30.600 --> 32:33.000
Because he's a loser
with no future

32:33.000 --> 32:34.280
from the wrong side of town.

32:34.280 --> 32:36.200
She said that?

32:36.200 --> 32:37.640
Well, I'm paraphrasing.

32:37.640 --> 32:39.440
Well, she couldn't
be more wrong.

32:39.440 --> 32:41.800
I mean, he works harder than
anyone I know.

32:41.800 --> 32:44.880
I know that.

32:44.880 --> 32:47.600
What am I gonna do?

32:47.600 --> 32:50.680
Lola, it's simple.

32:51.360 --> 32:54.200
You're going to do
what your mother says.

32:54.200 --> 32:55.520
What?

32:55.520 --> 32:57.480
Or not.

32:57.480 --> 33:01.000
Life isn't difficult. It's human
nature to complicate it.

33:01.000 --> 33:04.200
Life is just a series
of choices.

33:04.200 --> 33:08.240
You either choose this or that.

33:08.240 --> 33:10.040
What if I don't like either?

33:11.760 --> 33:13.720
Then you choose the other.

33:23.920 --> 33:25.640
-We haven't --
-Do the voice.

33:25.640 --> 33:27.480
[ Laughs ]

33:27.480 --> 33:29.600
[ Deep voice ]
We haven't been introduced.

33:29.600 --> 33:34.600
My name is Bowman,
Jonathan Bowman.

33:34.600 --> 33:39.000
When she spoke her voice
was like listening to smoke.

33:39.000 --> 33:41.520
Ah, geez, I don't know
how smoke sounds.

33:41.520 --> 33:44.640
All whispery and smoky,
and, you know.

33:44.640 --> 33:46.720
[ Coughs ]

33:46.720 --> 33:48.560
Not like that.

33:48.560 --> 33:50.840
Okay.

33:50.840 --> 33:56.040
[ High-pitched ] My name is
Genevieve Bouchard, Mr. Bowman.

33:56.040 --> 33:58.960
And I...

33:59.680 --> 34:01.120
[ Normal voice ] Genevieve?

34:03.520 --> 34:05.200
You know what?

34:05.200 --> 34:07.960
It is getting late,
isn't it, stinker?

34:07.960 --> 34:10.280
I'll tell you what, why don't
you go up and clean your teeth,

34:10.280 --> 34:12.200
and then I will come up
and tuck you in?

34:12.200 --> 34:14.720
[ Groans ]

34:14.720 --> 34:17.600
I know, I know.

34:17.600 --> 34:18.680
Love you.

34:18.680 --> 34:20.360
LIBERTY: Love you, too.

34:25.600 --> 34:28.000
[ Typing ]

34:43.600 --> 34:47.320
[ Cellphone buzzing ]

34:48.560 --> 34:50.080
Hello.

34:50.080 --> 34:51.200
They're not named after
old films.

34:51.200 --> 34:53.240
-What aren't?
-The wigs.

34:53.240 --> 34:56.920
They're named after love
interests in the dad's books.

34:56.920 --> 34:58.520
22 books and 22 wigs.

34:58.520 --> 34:59.880
Why didn't I see that?

34:59.880 --> 35:01.760
Yeah, see that's wigs and books,

35:01.760 --> 35:04.960
but where does embroidery
come into play?

35:04.960 --> 35:06.280
I have an idea about that.

35:06.280 --> 35:08.800
Meet me at Susan's
at 10:00, okay?

35:08.800 --> 35:10.360
I got to go.

35:11.480 --> 35:13.840
-[ Beeps ]
-Rude.

35:16.400 --> 35:19.240
Can I interest madam
in a little more red wine?

35:19.240 --> 35:20.800
Always.

35:24.200 --> 35:25.680
Now...

35:31.200 --> 35:32.720
Okay.

35:32.720 --> 35:33.760
[ Camera shutter clicks ]

35:33.760 --> 35:35.520
You have a good day.

35:35.520 --> 35:36.680
[ Camera shutter clicks ]

35:36.680 --> 35:38.040
Oh, that's it, fella.

35:38.040 --> 35:40.240
Work it, own it.

35:40.240 --> 35:42.960
[ Chuckles ] You are so screwed.

35:43.640 --> 35:45.320
[ Camera shutter clicks ]

35:47.360 --> 35:49.240
Oh, I have you there, Ray,
you prick.

35:53.000 --> 35:55.520
-Sabrina.
-Got it.

35:55.520 --> 35:56.680
"Laugh, Said the Widow."

35:56.680 --> 35:59.480
And last one, Mary.

35:59.480 --> 36:03.480
Medusa in a bikini.
Missing one is Rebecca.

36:03.480 --> 36:05.680
"Bombay Blonde."

36:15.920 --> 36:17.640
What is going on? Tell me.

36:17.640 --> 36:19.200
HARRY: It's a treasure hunt.

36:19.200 --> 36:20.720
Your mother really did love
her games.

36:20.720 --> 36:23.400
See, the names in the wigs
are the names of

36:23.400 --> 36:25.280
the love interests
in your father's books.

36:25.280 --> 36:27.720
HARRY: So the wig that Bella
got in the will,

36:27.720 --> 36:31.680
Granny Susan's Fun Time Wig, it
had the name Rebecca sewn in it.

36:31.680 --> 36:34.840
Rebecca leads to
a specific book.

36:34.840 --> 36:36.360
And the dates on
the embroideries

36:36.360 --> 36:37.760
are wrong on purpose.

36:37.760 --> 36:38.920
It's a book code.

36:38.920 --> 36:41.400
See, each date has two mistakes.

36:41.400 --> 36:43.000
Well, beginning
in historical order

36:43.000 --> 36:45.920
because, well, why not,
the first one would be

36:45.920 --> 36:49.360
the signing of the Magna Carta,
15th of June, 1215.

36:49.360 --> 36:52.000
15-06-12-15.

36:52.000 --> 36:57.440
But your mother embroidered
15-11-1315.

36:57.440 --> 37:01.760
Which is November instead of
June, 11 instead of 6.

37:01.760 --> 37:04.000
So it'll be on the 11th page.

37:04.000 --> 37:06.200
Yeah, see and the second mistake
is in the year.

37:06.200 --> 37:09.360
1315 instead of 1215.

37:09.360 --> 37:10.880
3 instead of 2.

37:10.880 --> 37:12.840
That's in reference
to the third word.

37:12.840 --> 37:17.240
So, the third word
on the 11th page is...

37:17.240 --> 37:18.720
"ash."

37:18.720 --> 37:21.040
And the ninth page, ninth word.

37:21.040 --> 37:22.280
Croft.

37:22.280 --> 37:25.040
26th page, 12th word.

37:25.040 --> 37:26.200
Holland.

37:26.200 --> 37:29.280
14th page, ninth word.

37:29.280 --> 37:33.400
-Somerset.
-And the first page 19th word.

37:33.400 --> 37:34.960
HARRY: Road.

37:34.960 --> 37:38.280
Ash croft Holland Somerset Road.

37:38.280 --> 37:40.480
So, we need to get
everyone together.

37:40.480 --> 37:43.440
We -- we -- we can't.
They've all gone back home.

37:43.440 --> 37:45.840
Jasper's in Paris,
and Chloe's in Edinburgh.

37:45.840 --> 37:47.360
We can do a video call.

37:47.360 --> 37:50.480
Uh, 2:00 today, right?

37:50.480 --> 37:53.120
Got it.
They're over in Ranelagh.

37:53.120 --> 37:55.920
-[ Line ringing ]
-It's ringing.

37:55.920 --> 37:58.280
RECEPTIONIST: Ashcroft Holland
Solicitors. How can I help?

37:58.280 --> 38:00.200
Yes, hello.

38:00.200 --> 38:02.960
Um, I'm representing the family
of the late Susan Henderson.

38:02.960 --> 38:05.440
Is there someone I could
talk to about her estate?

38:05.440 --> 38:09.200
RECEPTIONIST: Uh, yes.
One moment please.

38:09.200 --> 38:11.400
After this, I have
to see Charlie.

38:11.400 --> 38:12.520
We'll need his help.

38:12.520 --> 38:14.760
And I need you to do two things.

38:14.760 --> 38:16.640
One's a little dangerous.

38:16.640 --> 38:18.800
Cool. Danger is my middle name.

38:18.800 --> 38:20.360
[ Groans ]

38:22.200 --> 38:24.760
[ Siren wailing ]

38:33.920 --> 38:37.000
VIVIAN: You cheating bastard.

38:37.000 --> 38:40.040
How could you?
I mean, of all the women?

38:40.040 --> 38:42.040
It ends now.

38:42.040 --> 38:43.640
This second.

38:43.640 --> 38:45.560
Immediately, do I make myself
clear, Raymond?

38:47.960 --> 38:49.520
I'm sorry it ends
when did you say?

38:49.520 --> 38:51.600
A week Thursday?
I'll check my calendar.

38:51.600 --> 38:53.120
Don't!

38:54.840 --> 38:57.800
I will end your career.

38:57.800 --> 39:00.880
Is she worth that, huh?

39:00.880 --> 39:03.760
No. I didn't think so.

39:03.760 --> 39:05.320
Now do as I say.

39:09.280 --> 39:11.760
[ Door opens, closes ]

39:14.560 --> 39:20.000
Do you remember when you
used to spank my bottom, Yorgos?

39:20.000 --> 39:22.960
I haven't had
a good spanking in years.

39:29.200 --> 39:30.680
How are you fixed
for an hour from now?

39:30.680 --> 39:32.440
I need you to arrest someone.

39:32.440 --> 39:35.000
[ Groans ]
That's not how it works, Harry.

39:35.000 --> 39:37.520
Or course, I know.
Quite right, dear.

39:37.520 --> 39:41.520
But I do know who killed
Susan Henderson.

39:43.520 --> 39:45.480
[ Sighs ]

39:51.280 --> 39:53.240
Is everyone there?
Good. So, uh...

39:53.240 --> 39:54.440
Have you found out what
my mother did

39:54.440 --> 39:56.040
with the money or not?

39:56.040 --> 39:57.040
We have.

39:57.040 --> 40:00.040
Then tell us, right now.

40:00.040 --> 40:02.120
All in good time, Mr. Henderson.

40:02.120 --> 40:07.040
Um, now what this comes down to
is a case of really bad timing.

40:07.040 --> 40:09.520
No, dammit! You work for us.

40:09.520 --> 40:13.400
Now, do as I tell you,
answer my question.

40:13.400 --> 40:15.720
Very well, if you insist.

40:15.720 --> 40:18.880
What this comes down to
is a case of really bad timing.

40:18.880 --> 40:21.000
See, recently Bella asked Susan

40:21.000 --> 40:22.680
for an advance
on her inheritance

40:22.680 --> 40:24.480
so she could follow her dreams.

40:24.480 --> 40:26.400
And that got Susan thinking.

40:26.400 --> 40:28.600
And she decided to give you
all your inheritance

40:28.600 --> 40:31.960
now rather than waiting
till she died.

40:31.960 --> 40:34.880
I told you she didn't laugh me
out of the room, Chloe.

40:34.880 --> 40:38.640
Susan wanted to be around to see
all of you enjoy the money.

40:38.640 --> 40:41.560
But that still doesn't tell us
what she did with it.

40:41.560 --> 40:43.960
Well, what she did with it
was set up trust funds,

40:43.960 --> 40:46.200
one for each of you.

40:46.200 --> 40:48.080
[ Scoffs ]
Why didn't she tell us?

40:48.080 --> 40:50.240
She was going to
on that last call.

40:50.240 --> 40:53.200
W-w-wait, how -- how do you
know this?

40:53.200 --> 40:55.520
Well, because we spoke
to her solicitor today.

40:55.520 --> 40:58.600
Oh, you didn't.
I spoke to him this afternoon.

40:58.600 --> 41:00.240
Not the family solicitor.

41:00.240 --> 41:02.000
She didn't go to him
because she wanted to do it

41:02.000 --> 41:05.400
as a game and knew he was too
much of a fuddy-duddy to agree.

41:05.400 --> 41:07.000
Wait, wait, wait, we are talking

41:07.000 --> 41:09.520
about a multi-million
Euro inheritance,

41:09.520 --> 41:12.760
and you're saying my mother
turned it into a game?

41:12.760 --> 41:14.720
Yeah, a treasure hunt.

41:14.720 --> 41:19.000
See, your mother was about
to give you the first clue

41:19.000 --> 41:20.880
when the killer struck, see.

41:20.880 --> 41:24.840
I have something to say.
I have come to a decision.

41:24.840 --> 41:26.360
-Who's there with you, Mammy?
-Who is that?

41:26.360 --> 41:29.200
Why, no one. I'm here on my own.

41:29.200 --> 41:32.480
If only you'd waited
a few minutes.

41:32.480 --> 41:34.440
Who are you talking to?

41:34.440 --> 41:38.160
Are you suggesting one of us
murdered her?

41:38.160 --> 41:41.040
If these two clowns can work out
"the code,"

41:41.040 --> 41:43.040
I most certainly can.

41:43.040 --> 41:44.600
Oh, well, it's not that simple.

41:44.600 --> 41:47.680
You see, one forfeits
an inheritance

41:47.680 --> 41:49.720
when you murder
the person to get it.

41:49.720 --> 41:51.920
It was a burglar.

41:51.920 --> 41:55.200
No one here murdered her.
We were all on the call.

41:55.200 --> 41:58.000
We couldn't be in
two places at once.

41:58.000 --> 42:00.600
Yeah, except one of you
wasn't on the call.

42:00.600 --> 42:05.000
We saw one another.
We talked to one another.

42:05.000 --> 42:06.720
That's not quite true, is it?

42:06.720 --> 42:08.120
Cast your minds back.

42:08.120 --> 42:10.680
You started by singing
"Happy Birthday."

42:10.680 --> 42:13.200
As the song ended, one of you
tried to carry on with

42:13.200 --> 42:14.640
"For She's a Jolly Good Fellow."

42:14.640 --> 42:16.040
That was you, Chloe.

42:16.040 --> 42:17.480
And Jasper cut you off.

42:17.480 --> 42:19.000
Yes, I did.

42:19.000 --> 42:21.240
I remember that because I felt
it was my duty

42:21.240 --> 42:25.480
to say a few words, and then
we talked about my divorce.

42:25.480 --> 42:28.520
I-I made a cracking joke.
I mean, I-I was there.

42:28.520 --> 42:29.800
We were all there.

42:29.800 --> 42:31.720
We all talked.

42:31.720 --> 42:33.480
Or Bella didn't.

42:33.480 --> 42:35.160
Well, it wasn't me.

42:35.160 --> 42:37.400
We have a recording,
as you've seen.

42:37.400 --> 42:40.400
It took us a while to see
what Alistair saw straight away.

42:40.400 --> 42:43.760
Listen, if you're suggesting
that my daughter was responsible

42:43.760 --> 42:45.960
for what happened,
then you have completely --

42:45.960 --> 42:47.640
Uh, uh, we weren't saying that.

42:47.640 --> 42:50.680
Now, Bella was there.
She laughed at Noah's joke.

42:50.680 --> 42:53.240
Celia. Ha.

42:53.240 --> 42:55.000
She never interacted
with any of us.

42:55.000 --> 42:57.880
I'm 78, you little shit!

42:57.880 --> 43:00.280
You think I strangled my sister?

43:00.280 --> 43:02.200
It wasn't Celia either.

43:02.200 --> 43:03.560
So who was it?

43:03.560 --> 43:06.440
It was...

43:06.440 --> 43:07.720
Chloe.

43:07.720 --> 43:10.920
-What?
-[ Laughs ]

43:10.920 --> 43:13.480
No. I...

43:13.480 --> 43:17.600
I mean, you said yourself
that I cut her off, huh?

43:17.600 --> 43:20.480
Yeah, and then she sulked.
She didn't interact any more.

43:20.480 --> 43:22.640
It -- it doesn't matter
if she didn't interact.

43:22.640 --> 43:25.600
I could see her.
I was looking straight at her.

43:25.600 --> 43:28.200
Exactly, thank you, Stefanie.

43:28.200 --> 43:30.480
No, you were looking
at a recording played

43:30.480 --> 43:32.080
as if it was live.

43:32.080 --> 43:33.520
No, impossible because
she couldn't have known

43:33.520 --> 43:35.520
Jasper was going
to talk over her,

43:35.520 --> 43:37.400
not at that precise
moment anyway.

43:37.400 --> 43:39.000
Not unless they planned it.

43:39.000 --> 43:40.760
Why would they...?

43:40.760 --> 43:44.920
Jasper, Chloe, do you want
to tell her, or shall I?

43:44.920 --> 43:47.640
Jasper, stop her.

43:47.640 --> 43:49.600
It's because Chloe is
the younger woman

43:49.600 --> 43:52.760
with whom Jasper
is cheating on his wife.

43:52.760 --> 43:55.600
That is sick.

43:55.600 --> 43:57.080
She's his niece.

43:57.080 --> 43:58.640
Adopted, not a blood relative.

43:58.640 --> 43:59.880
Not actually illegal.

43:59.880 --> 44:01.600
Just icky.

44:01.600 --> 44:04.080
She was in Edinburgh, she...

44:04.080 --> 44:06.960
Oh, she was no more in Edinburgh
than Jasper was in Paris.

44:06.960 --> 44:08.880
In reality, both were in a suite

44:08.880 --> 44:11.400
in the M Hotel mere minutes
away from Susan's.

44:11.400 --> 44:14.000
And that's what
Alistair realized

44:14.000 --> 44:15.680
when he watched
back the recording.

44:15.680 --> 44:18.440
FERGUS: See, Jasper and Chloe
both brought items from home

44:18.440 --> 44:20.840
in order to recreate what you
would normally

44:20.840 --> 44:22.400
see on these calls.

44:22.400 --> 44:25.080
There's a lamp that's always
behind Chloe,

44:25.080 --> 44:28.080
and maybe it got broken
or maybe she just forgot it.

44:28.080 --> 44:30.200
And they decided no one
would notice

44:30.200 --> 44:32.480
if they used the one
in the room.

44:32.480 --> 44:34.000
HARRY: That one that's
behind you now Chloe.

44:34.000 --> 44:36.240
The thing is those lamps
are bespoke,

44:36.240 --> 44:38.680
designed for the hotel
by a local man.

44:38.680 --> 44:40.240
Yeah, there was
an article about it

44:40.240 --> 44:43.000
in the hotel's
in house magazine.

44:43.000 --> 44:45.400
Alistair had a copy in his flat.

44:45.400 --> 44:48.760
He contacted Chloe, said he
wanted money to keep quiet.

44:48.760 --> 44:51.400
She agreed, but when
the family solicitor

44:51.400 --> 44:55.360
said there wasn't any,
they realized they couldn't pay.

44:55.360 --> 44:58.240
Which meant that Alistair
had to die, too.

44:58.240 --> 45:00.560
So Chloe lured him
to the rooftop bar,

45:00.560 --> 45:02.800
and Jasper pushed him off.

45:02.800 --> 45:04.720
Ha!

45:04.720 --> 45:06.200
Now, Charlie.

45:06.200 --> 45:08.000
[ Jasper laughing ]

45:10.840 --> 45:12.200
Jasper, do something!
Make it stop.

45:12.200 --> 45:15.200
Get off.

45:15.200 --> 45:17.920
Jasper Henderson,
Chloe Henderson,

45:17.920 --> 45:20.440
you're under arrest for
the murder of Susan Henderson.

45:20.440 --> 45:22.000
Stupid girl!

45:22.560 --> 45:24.520
[ Laughs ]

45:27.240 --> 45:29.800
Oh, well that was more fun
than usual.

45:29.800 --> 45:32.040
[ Laughs ]

45:34.200 --> 45:36.040
[ Birds chirping ]

45:38.360 --> 45:40.360
[ Exhales deeply ]

45:42.840 --> 45:45.360
I can't. You do it.

45:45.360 --> 45:47.200
[ Sighs ]

45:47.200 --> 45:49.200
[ Pounding on door ]

45:49.200 --> 45:51.680
Oh, bugger, what now?

45:55.280 --> 45:57.200
[ Sighs ]

46:00.400 --> 46:02.880
I couldn't take it anymore.

46:02.880 --> 46:04.560
What?

46:07.600 --> 46:10.680
What the -- mm.

46:10.680 --> 46:12.560
Champagne I think.

46:15.800 --> 46:17.760
[ Pounding on door ]

46:17.760 --> 46:19.480
Oh, bloody hell, now what?

46:22.680 --> 46:23.920
-Ah.
-Uh...

46:23.920 --> 46:25.200
Thought you'd like to know,

46:25.200 --> 46:27.440
we got a full confession
from Chloe and...

46:27.440 --> 46:29.000
[ Cork pops ]

46:30.360 --> 46:33.000
Let's pour -- Charlie?

46:34.600 --> 46:36.680
HARRY: Oh.

46:36.680 --> 46:38.560
No.

46:38.640 --> 46:40.400
No.

46:40.400 --> 46:42.040
[ Groans ]

46:42.040 --> 46:43.520
No!

46:43.520 --> 46:44.480
[ Groans ]

46:44.480 --> 46:46.040
Grab your coat.

46:49.440 --> 46:52.200
[ Sighs ]

46:52.200 --> 46:54.520
June, bring the wine.

46:54.520 --> 46:56.200
All of the wine.

46:56.200 --> 46:58.400
Reckon they've noticed
you've left?

46:58.400 --> 47:00.800
Oh, I don't want
to think about it.

47:00.800 --> 47:02.440
Come on, envelope.

47:13.200 --> 47:15.000
Well?
